\begin_layout Section*
Question 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
a.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively, we would expect the supply curve to shift to the left.
 Without CB intervention, the price would rise and the output will decrease.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
b.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
(1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Start in a steady state: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=x=i=u=v=f=p_{t}^{*}=i_{t}^{*}=z=0;\,\,e-p=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
(2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A positive shock in 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}$
\end_inset

 is introduced.
 The shock affects only the current period, thus the expected values in
 the next period are the steady state values:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{x}_{t+1}=\hat{\pi}_{t+1}=0;\,\,\hat{e}_{t+1}=\hat{p}_{t+1}=p_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
(3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The values of the lagged values are irrelevant, assume 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t-1}=e_{t-1}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
(4)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substitute (2) and (3) in the equations of the model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(S)\,\,p_{t}=\kappa x_{t}+u_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(D)\,\,x_{t}=-i_{t}+\vartheta(e_{t}-p_{t})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(TR)\,\,i_{t}=\phi_{\pi}p_{t}+\phi_{x}x_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(UIP)\,\,e_{t}=\hat{e}_{t+1}-i_{t}+f_{t}=p_{t}-i_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
(5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substitute UIP into the demand equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(D)\,\,x_{t}=-i_{t}+\vartheta(p_{t}-i_{t}-p_{t})=-(1+\vartheta)i
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
(6)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substitute Taylor rule into the demand equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{t}=-(1+\vartheta)i=-(1+\vartheta)(\phi_{\pi}p_{t}+\phi_{x}x_{t});\,\,p_{t}=-\frac{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}{(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}}x_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
(7)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Find the equilibrium values by equating supply to demand:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa x_{t}+u_{t}=-\frac{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}{(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}}x_{t}\Rightarrow\left(\kappa+\frac{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}{(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}}\right)x_{t}=-u_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{t}=\frac{-u_{t}}{\kappa+\frac{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}{(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}}}=\frac{-u_{t}}{\frac{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}\kappa}{(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}}}=
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{-(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}u_{t}}{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}\kappa}<0
\]

\end_inset

Thus there is a negative effect on the output.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now find out the price level using the supply curve:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{t}=\kappa x_{t}+u_{t}=\frac{-(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}\kappa+1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}\kappa}{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}\kappa}u_{t}=\frac{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}\kappa}u_{t}>0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
(8)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Find the interest rate by substituting into Taylor rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i_{t}=\phi_{\pi}\frac{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}\kappa}u_{t}+\phi_{x}\frac{-(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}u_{t}}{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}\kappa}=
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\phi_{\pi}(1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x})u_{t}-(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}\phi_{\pi}u_{t}}{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}\kappa}=\frac{\phi_{\pi}u_{t}}{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}\kappa}>0
\]

\end_inset

Thus the interest rate goes up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
(9)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exchange rate is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{t}=\frac{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}\kappa}u_{t}-\frac{\phi_{\pi}u_{t}}{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}\kappa}=
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{(1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}-\phi_{\pi})u_{t}}{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}\kappa}
\]

\end_inset

Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\vartheta=0.3,\,\,\phi_{x}=0.5,\,\,\phi_{\pi}=1.5$
\end_inset

 we can conclude:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{t}=\frac{1+1.3\cdot0.5-1.5}{(+)}u_{t}>0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the effect on the exchange rate is positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
c.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be seen from the equations that a higher value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{x}$
\end_inset

: decreases the impact level (of the shock) on the output, increases the
 impact on price level, decreases the impact on the interest rate and decreases
 the impact on the exchange rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A higher value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\pi}$
\end_inset

: increases the impact level on the output (i.e the output will decrease
 by more), decreases the impact on price level, increases the impact on
 the interest rate and increases the impact on the exchange rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Question 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
a.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively, we would assume a decline in the world interest rate to lead
 to a decrease in the exchange rate (by the UIP equation), which is likely
 to impact the demand on domestic good, and shift the demand curve to the
 left.
 Wihtout CB intervention, price level and production output will decrease
 (movement along the supply curve).
\end_layout

