\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
(5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substitute UIP into the demand equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(D)\,\,x_{t}=-i_{t}+\vartheta(i_{t}^{*}+p_{t}-i_{t}-p_{t})=-(1+\vartheta)i+i_{t}^{*}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
(6)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substitute Taylor rule into the demand equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{t}=-(1+\vartheta)i+i_{t}^{*}=-(1+\vartheta)(\phi_{\pi}p_{t}+\phi_{x}x_{t})+i_{t}^{*};\,\,p_{t}=-\frac{(1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x})x_{t}-i_{t}^{*}}{(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
(7)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Find the equilibrium values by equating supply to demand:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa x_{t}=-\frac{(1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x})x_{t}-i_{t}^{*}}{(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}}\Rightarrow x_{t}=\frac{i_{t}^{*}}{\kappa(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}+1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus there is a negative effect on the output (the numerator is negative,
 while the denominator is positive).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The new price level is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\kappa i_{t}^{*}}{\kappa(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}+1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}<0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is negative as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
(8)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Find the interest rate by substituting into Taylor rule:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i_{t}=\phi_{\pi}p_{t}+\phi_{x}x_{t}=\phi_{\pi}\frac{\kappa i_{t}^{*}}{\kappa(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}+1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}+\phi_{x}\frac{i_{t}^{*}}{\kappa(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}+1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}=
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\frac{i_{t}^{*}(\phi_{\pi}\kappa+\phi_{x})}{\kappa(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}+1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}=\frac{(-)(+)}{(+)}<0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
thus the interest rate decreases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
(9)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exchange rate is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{t}=\frac{\kappa i_{t}^{*}}{\kappa(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}+1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}-\frac{i_{t}^{*}(\phi_{\pi}\kappa+\phi_{x})}{\kappa(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}+1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}=
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=0.65,\,\,\phi_{x}=0.5,\,\,\phi_{\pi}=1.5$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\frac{i_{t}^{*}(\kappa(1-\phi_{\pi})-\phi_{x})}{\kappa(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}+1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}=\frac{(-)(-)}{(+)}>0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the exchange rate increases.
\end_layout

